                                                                            <comments>
                            <comment id="251957" author="mhanafi" created="Wed, 24 Jul 2019 17:08:41 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;please close&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="246112" author="adilger" created="Sat, 20 Apr 2019 22:35:06 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;What version of e2fsprogs do you have installed? We recommend using the latest version, which is currently 1.44.5-wc1.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I don&apos;t think these messages are harmful, just a new check added since the last time you ran a full e2fsck, or possibly leftovers from the time the filesystem was formatted. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You can determine which files are affected by running &quot;&lt;tt&gt;debugfs -c -R &apos;ncheck 529673 529713 ...&apos; /dev/XXX&lt;/tt&gt;&quot; for the listed inode numbers, and/or &quot;&lt;tt&gt;debugfs -c -R &apos;stat &amp;lt;529673&amp;gt; /dev/XXX&lt;/tt&gt;&quot; to determine the pathname and timestamps/owners of the files. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Running a fixing e2fsck should be fine. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
